{"id":"5e9c0546774c2610387e4d69","title":"Artist Profile: Oliver Uwins","content":"<p>Oliver Uwins’ kinetic sculptures use modern day machines positioned, balanced, clamped and gaffer taped together to create the illusion of grainy, otherworldly film footage.</p><p> Quite literally using science to create fiction.</p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/65807673\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" title=\"Science Fiction Final Movie\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n<p>The ‘Rube Goldberg’-esq<a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> machines at first have a look of engineered pointlessness, but upon closer inspection as you peer, squat next to and move around the constructions- you come to realise the beauty behind the combinations. The various pieces of scanners, decks, lamps, stands and coils- spin, shake and connect, to create the beautiful, ephemeral sci-fi imagery shown on screen.</p>\n<p>Switching between the miniature camera points around the piece, the monitor displays what at first looks like a sparkling sky, turning out be a product of light bulbs swinging behind a piece of strategically place holey black card.</p>\n<p>With elements of Pipilotti Rist- the mix of technology and magic is mesmerising; you become transfixed watching things whirr and connect, waiting for the results on screen. The piece slowly reveals it’s own workings out to you, and it’s fascinating to watch.</p>\n\n\t\t<style type=\"text/css\">\n\t\t\t#gallery-1 {\n\t\t\t\tmargin: auto;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t#gallery-1 .gallery-item {\n\t\t\t\tfloat: left;\n\t\t\t\tmargin-top: 10px;\n\t\t\t\ttext-align: center;\n\t\t\t\twidth: 33%;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t#gallery-1 img {\n\t\t\t\tborder: 2px solid #cfcfcf;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t#gallery-1 .gallery-caption {\n\t\t\t\tmargin-left: 0;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t/* see gallery_shortcode() in wp-includes/media.php */\n\t\t</style>\n\t\t<div id='gallery-1' class='gallery galleryid-23080 gallery-columns-3 gallery-siz